I agree with the sentiments of the parents. CRISPR technology is remarkable and truely amazing, but when we start using it on humans, it starts to objectify humans. We start acting like we can have "customizable" babies and we think we are offering opportunities to kids who need it. But in reality, there are many unseen opportunities taken away when we wipe away imperfections in the the genes. Such as humanity itself. One of the very unique things that make us human is that we have to deal with the imperfections that God has given us, as well as deal with others imperfections. Even if you don't believe that God exists, you have to admit that there is an obvious element of "playing god" by picking and choosing. Pick and choose all you want, there will be consequences to upsetting the truth -- which is, that all humans, no matter their issues and problems, are valued and loved. CRISPR human gene editing just chips away at that value, one gene at a time.

As a Mom who've birthed premature children and even burying one as a result, I'm glad gene editing is a discussion. However, as a Believer and a real person with morals and ethics, I'm strongly against altering anything God created. "Editing", "Cloning", or the like are in my eyes, man trying, yet again, to be God although every time, something unexpected happens as a result and only harms the person/animal/insect/land/water etc on the receiving end of people's experiments to control life. I marked that I feel warmth for scientists 50-60% of the time only because my living son aspires to be a Scientist, specifically a Molecular Biologist working with cells. He's always been my Science genius so I can't fully knock the profession because it does do good some times. If I didn't include my son in this rating, the score would've been much lower. The age old saying in my Black community/upbringing is still relevant today, as always, in that we "don't need to fix what's not broken". Thank you for this video and I believe as I've taught my son to believe, if it's only for the good and not harm of others, science can be accepted and celebrated but trying to "fine tune" what no one asked for is a waste of great talent and waste of already valued resources. I thoroughly enjoyed this video and am glad Ruthie and her Parents understand the importance of just letting our kids be whomever they were created to be.
